OverviewBoard MembersCommittees



Executive Profile
Thomas F. McLarty IIIPresident and Co-founder, McLarty AssociatesAgeTotal Calculated CompensationThis person is connected to 11 Board Members in 11 different organizations across 13 different industries.See Board Relationships70--
Background

		Mr. Thomas F. McLarty, III, also known as Mack, serves as the President at McLarty Associates. He serves as an Executive Vice Chairman at RLJ-McLarty-Landers Automotive Holdings, LLC since October 10, 2016. Mr. McLarty serves as an Advisor at Verdeo Group, Inc. Mr. McLarty serves as Senior Advisor of The Carlyle Group LP and at Covington & Burling. He is a Co-Founder and Chairman of McLarty Associates and serves as its PresidentMr. McLarty began his business career building ... McLarty Leasing Systems (McLarty Companies). Mr. McLarty serves as the Non- Executive Chairman and prior to April 2005, Mr. McLarty was the Chief Executive Officer of the McLarty Companies. He serves as the Chairman at McLarty Capital Partners LLC. In addition, Mr. McLarty is Senior Counselor to the Center for Strategic and International Studies, he serves as a Senior International Fellow at the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. Mr. McLarty was a Senior Advisor at Monument Capital Group, LLC. He served as Chairman, Chief Executive Officer, Member of the Board of Directors of CenterPoint Energy Arkla. In 1976, he became the youngest member ever elected to the Board of Directors of the Arkla Gas/Arkla, Inc. Mr. McLarty served as Special Limited Partner at Forstmann Little & Co. He was Co-Founder of Kissinger McLarty Capital Group. In 1985 he became Arkla's Chairman and Chief Executive Officer and served in that position until joining the White House in 1993. Mr. McLarty spent a decade as Chairman and Chief Executive Officer of the firm. Mr. McLarty was Co-Founder of Rubikon Partners. He also worked with President Carter, was appointed to the National Petroleum Council and the National Council on Environmental Quality by President George H.W. Bush and served on the St. Louis Federal Reserve Board from 1989 until joining the Clinton Administration in 1992. Mr. McLarty was affiliated with the Clinton White House from 1993 through 1997, during which time he acted in several capacities. He was appointed to two commissions by President Bush and served under President Clinton in several key positions including the White House Chief of Staff from 1993 to 1994, Counselor to the President, and "special envoy to the Americas" in which capacity he was a key mover and shaker in the creation of NAFTA and the Free Trade Area of the Americas (FTAA), with over five years of service in the President's Cabinet and on the National Economic Council. As White House Chief of Staff, Mr. McLarty helped enact the historic 1993 deficit reduction package, the North American Free Trade Agreement, the Family and Medical Leave law and the landmark welfare reform legislation that enabled more than 6.8 million people to move from welfare to work. He served as a key liaison to Clinton for Rockefeller's Council in the implementation of this trade agreement and also organized the successful 1994 Summit of the Americas in Miami, which ultimately led to his appointment as Special Envoy for the Americas in 1997. As Counselor to the President, he advised on a broad range of international and domestic issues. Mr. McLarty traveled to the Persian Gulf on the President's behalf to build financial support for the Bosnian peace process, led the U.S. delegation to the inauguration of South Korean President Kim Dae-jung, signed the peace accords that brought peace to Guatemala for the first time in three decades. He planned U.S. participation in the 1998 "Summit of the Americas" in Santiago and participated in several G-7 and APEC Summits. Mr. McLarty began his political career in 1969 when he was elected to the State Legislature of Arkansas and served as Chairman of the state Democratic Party from 1974 to 1976 and later served as Treasurer for both David Pryor's and Bill Clinton's gubernatorial campaigns. He was appointed by President Bush to the National Petroleum Council and the National Council on Environmental Quality. Upon leaving the White House in July 1998, Mr. McLarty became President of an international advisory firm. In 2007, he launched RLJ-McLarty-Landers. He served as Chairman of RLJ-McLarty-Landers Automotive Holdings, LLC and its Vice Chairman until October 10, 2016. Mr. McLarty served as Vice Chairman of Asbury Automotive Group, Inc. from May 2002 to July 12, 2006. He serves on the boards of the Bush Clinton Katrina Fund, the Council of the Americas, the Inter-American Dialogue, Religions for Peace, Ford's Theatre and the Center for the Study of the Presidency. Mr. McLarty has been a Director of Union Pacific Corporation since November 16, 2006. He is an Advisor at Leeds Equity Patners, LLC. He is an Advisor of Blackstreet Capital Management, LLC and Leeds Equity Partners, LLC. He serves as an Advisory Board Member of Monument Capital Group, LLC, CODA Automotive, Inc., DB Climate Change Advisors. Mr. McLarty served as Director of Commercial National Bank (Tiffin, Ohio) and Entergy Corporation. He was a Member of Advisory Board at Diligence London and Emerging Markets Private Equity Association. He served as Director of Greenstreet Acquisition Corp. Mr. McLarty served as Chairman of Norte-Sur Partners. He served as Non-Executive Chairman and Non Executive Director of Asbury Automotive Arkansas LLC from April 1, 2005 to July 12, 2006. He served as Director of Acxiom Corporation from 1999 to August 2, 2010 and Convoy Solutions, LLC and IdleAire, Inc since May 2006. Mr. McLarty served as Director of Ross University Management, Inc. Mr. McLarty is the recipient of the Secretary of State's Distinguished Service Medal, presented by Madeleine Albright; the Order of the Aztec Eagle, presented at Los Pinos by Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo; the Fair Share Award from the NAACP; the highest civilian honors of Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Mexico, Nicaragua, Panama and Venezuela; and the Center for the Study of the Presidency Distinguished Service Award. He has been honored with the National Conference for Community and Justice Award and the American Natural Gas Association Humanitarian Award Public Service Award. He is a frequent public speaker and has published numerous articles on U.S. trade and foreign policy. He has a distinguished record of business leadership and public service, including various roles advising three U.S. President: Bill Clinton, George H. W. Bush and Jimmy Carter. Mr. McLarty was awarded an Honorary Doctorate from his alma mater in 2000. He graduated, summa cum laude, with a degree in Business Administration from the University of Arkansas in 1969.Read Full Background




